-- PRESS DIGEST - Bulgaria - Aug 21
-- 
-- Thu Aug 21, 2014 03:13AM EDT
-- None



SOFIA, Aug 21 (Reuters) - These are some of the main stories in Bulgarian newspapers on Thursday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

-- Twenty two parties and seven coalitions will run in Bulgaria's early elections on October 5, the central electoral commission said. Some 45 parties and coalition set a new record by running in last year's parliamentary elections (Trud, Standart, Sega, Presa, Monitor -- A 41-year-old businessman, a chairman of an agriculture cooperative, was shot dead in front of his home the Bulgarian town of Botevgrad, the interior ministry said (Standart, Presa, Monitor, 24 Chasa, Duma). -- The government will allocate 16 million levs (10.85 million US dollar) to municipalities for the prevention, management and overcoming the consequences of natural disasters. The municipalities of Varna and Dobrich, which suffered the worst damages from the floods in June, will receive more than 1.8 million levs while the municipality of Mizia, which is still recovering from the floods, will get 1 million levs (Trud, Sega).  -- Some 53 percent of Bulgarians do not trust the banking system in the country, compared to 41 percent in July, according to a survey conducted by Gallup International between 1 and 6 of August. Lack of trust in Bulgarian financial institutions is on the rise for second straight month (Monitor, Duma). -- A dozen US Air Force F-15s and some 180 personnel have been deployed at Graf Ignatievo air base in southern Bulgaria to take part in a bilateral exercise with the Bulgarian Air Force (24 Chasa, Sega). -- The printing of 60 million new banknotes this year, a move that was at the centre of speculations this week, has been included in the central bank's budget for 2014. The central bank doubled the number of new bills compared to previous year levels as it needed to replace more outdated notes and keep reserves full (Capital daily, 24 Chasa, Sega).